WEBVTT

00:03.794 --> 00:07.481
18th of December. No, I'll take it back. 20th of 
December. 20th

00:11.929 --> 00:19.183
of December.

00:19.544 --> 00:20.145
Tell me about that. This was shortly after we 
deployed to Kunming. Prior to that, the Japanese

00:29.174 --> 00:33.798
had taken over so-called French Indochina at that 
time. They were operating a training base out of

00:33.818 --> 00:38.643
Hanoi to train their bomber pilots. And they had 
used the route from Hanoi to Kualian and to Kunming

00:39.383 --> 00:59.181
to bomb those cities, Kunming being a key city in 
the southern part of China, and also a big air base,

00:39.383 --> 00:59.181
and Kualian being another main supply base of the 
southern part of China, the south central part.

00:59.667 --> 01:01.830
And they had no opposition whatsoever. They sent 
me green crews up there, just bombing the city and

01:02.190 --> 01:07.937
the air base, trying to hit the air base. So when we 
got up there, that's one of the things we began to

01:07.957 --> 01:12.923
wait for. Well, as I say, we went up on the 14th and on 
the 20th. Now, I'd been on, as soon as we got up

01:16.027 --> 01:25.619
there, we went off on some scramble missions, 
expecting them the very next day, 15th, 16th,

01:16.027 --> 01:25.619
17th, and this was full of that for a while. So you 
were waiting for the bombers to hit you from Hanoi,

01:29.283 --> 01:34.290
but they didn't. We know for a fact that several 
raids took off and shortly after they got over the

01:34.310 --> 01:43.424
Chinese border, about halfway up the turnaround 
went back. Why is that? We know they had their own

01:44.505 --> 01:53.799
intelligence contacts in Kunming and they knew we 
were up there and they knew we had scrambled to get

01:44.505 --> 01:53.799
in the air. As a matter of fact, we had a Chinese spy 
on the hillside right opposite the air base at

01:58.662 --> 02:01.425
Hanoi. We knew exactly when they took off. And we 
also had in China, and that's one thing that

02:04.448 --> 02:24.109
General Chennault helped the Chinese develop in 
the late 30s, was a ground observer core system

02:04.448 --> 02:24.109
where the Chinese—we attempted to do that here in 
the earlier days in NORAD and ADC in the United

02:04.448 --> 02:24.109
States, which was useless. But over there, that's 
all they had, and the ground observer core worked

02:24.129 --> 02:27.673
with their meet telephone and signal systems, get 
word about an air raid coming up to Kunming, and

02:27.873 --> 02:34.485
that's how we were alerted. That's what we 
scrambled on. Eventually, they got a few radars

02:36.489 --> 02:51.737
over there through the land-leash system, but we 
got word on the morning of the 20th that the raid had

02:36.489 --> 02:51.737
taken off, and it was, I think it was 14 bombers.

02:57.792 --> 02:58.894
Ten bombers. Ten bombers. Ten Japanese bombers 
were en route. So you scrambled. We had about

03:04.682 --> 03:08.247
20,000 feet just approaching Kunming. So you 
scrambled. We knew they were on their way up, and I

03:10.831 --> 03:19.564
think we were at 20,000 feet in an area southeast of 
Kunming.

03:24.387 --> 03:30.112
I think we had 14 airplanes. We had to divide what we 
shot down by 14 people to get credit for our $500. We

03:36.979 --> 03:37.620
know this. Not one single one of those 10 airplanes 
ever got back across the Chinese border. No

03:42.124 --> 03:43.545
kidding. You nailed all of them. But we didn't 
account for them. In other words, the pilot didn't

03:47.149 --> 03:50.732
come back and say, I shot this one down, I shot that 
one. I came back and claimed two probables. It was

03:54.196 --> 03:55.298
my first combat. I had gotten so close to one, you 
know, my ego was like a toilet bowl. We just

03:59.083 --> 03:59.944
couldn't wait. And once the fighting started... 
Well, tell me when it started. Tell me about that.

04:06.794 --> 04:07.936
We climbed up. We knew they were coming. And the 
usual taxes, we'd climb up to altitude about

04:09.999 --> 04:14.145
20,000 feet. Now, you're getting higher than 
20,000 feet in a P-40, and, you know, you just have

04:14.165 --> 04:18.351
to operate at max volume. You don't have any 
reserves. And generally, the Japanese never flew

04:19.872 --> 04:23.276
above about 18,000 feet. So that gave us about 
2,000 foot altitude, which is all we needed. Well,

04:28.261 --> 04:31.905
coming down on top of them, you know, you'd pick up 
speed. And we'd have a band of speed, and I'd hit and

04:32.766 --> 04:40.735
run and come back, hit and run, peel off, come back, 
hit and run. And we finally saw this formation. All

04:44.039 --> 04:49.845
of them were in one formation of ten of them, a V. And 
of course, they had the right to come in. We

04:50.838 --> 04:52.239
immediately started attacking them. Once we 
started the attack, we were in elements of four,

04:52.380 --> 04:59.687
about, I think it was fourteen airplanes. And 
three or four in each? Four in each section, so it

05:01.069 --> 05:03.872
had to be two of us separate. And which ones in the V 
did you strike out first? Well, whenever, the

05:08.116 --> 05:12.781
minute we saw them, we started after them. Well, of 
course, all fourteen airplanes didn't arrive at

05:12.801 --> 05:15.684
the same time. See, in the formation we'd have, 
we'd have what's called The attack section would

05:19.593 --> 05:21.616
be four. There would be a support section about 
maybe 1,000 feet higher than them, a little behind

05:22.097 --> 05:27.484
them. Yeah. And then the reserve, another four at 
the top altitude, maybe 1,000 feet above, still

05:28.105 --> 05:34.074
further behind them. Sure. And, of course, 
everybody's looking, and we're flying back into

05:34.734 --> 05:41.184
loose formation to stand together to keep the 
airplanes within sight of each other. Once you saw

05:41.304 --> 05:45.129
the formation, you know, you pass a word, and 
everybody sees the formation. Sure. Well, then,

05:45.490 --> 05:49.195
of course, everybody pushes forward and gets 
there and maybe checks their guns even. And then we

05:49.478 --> 05:58.791
start, well of course, the closest flights of one, 
that's another thing that was peculiar to some.

05:59.612 --> 06:06.422
The first guy that got there was the first guy, I 
mean the one nearest was always the first one that

05:59.612 --> 06:06.422
got there. And from then on, boy, it was a fight 
about getting in your position. I've had to be

06:09.907 --> 06:16.817
amongst the pilots to get the attack, to make the 
first attack on the bomber. It was that eager. The

06:19.567 --> 06:23.332
first airplane, of course, in the lead, the boys 
would see him at the same time. He's the first one to

06:23.352 --> 06:25.055
go make the attack. Well, the rest of them then come 
by, and then, you know, you're peeling around to

06:25.075 --> 06:28.439
come back. And from then on, boy, it's a fight as to 
who's going to do it, like a bunch of chickens

06:28.520 --> 06:37.292
getting up there, birds, I mean, as to who's going 
to get in there and make that attack. And several

06:37.312 --> 06:48.848
times, I remember just about ready to, you know, my 
attack, to start firing, here's a P-40 coming and

06:37.312 --> 06:48.848
slip, you know, he turned and turned, and he 
slipped right in front of me, and I couldn't shoot.

06:48.963 --> 06:51.967
because he was trying to get in there and shoot too. 
We were just absolutely swarming all of them.

06:53.990 --> 06:55.031
That's the correct word. Just swarming. And 
whether it was another guy flying on my wing, I was

06:56.233 --> 07:01.300
letting him fly forward. You were in the attack 
four. I didn't know yet. You were in the attack

07:03.462 --> 07:04.524
four. What about the other eight now? Pretty soon 
they all came. They couldn't stay out. Oh, no, all

07:10.612 --> 07:12.334
of them. I don't know who shot who down, but I do know 
I came back and had some... I had some holes in my

07:18.730 --> 07:26.583
rear right tail fin, tail stabilizer, and I had to 
have those patched up. And I claimed two

07:26.603 --> 07:34.916
probables, but we saw about four airplanes go down 
during the time we was fighting them. Actually saw

07:34.936 --> 07:39.544
four fall out of formation, because they 
immediately turned and started running. But we

07:40.626 --> 07:45.193
got word from our intelligence that not one single 
airplane of those got back to base. But we only

07:46.439 --> 07:48.742
claimed, I think we claimed credit for four. And we 
divided the four 2,000 bucks among 14 of us,

07:49.303 --> 07:55.791
because we're not sure, you know, who knocked who 
down. And subsequent fights, particularly

07:56.813 --> 08:05.504
between fighters and fighters, you know, where 
you're maneuvering, you know whether you're

07:56.813 --> 08:05.504
going to shoot this guy down or not, because you're 
the only one behind him. Now, did you have a camera

08:05.524 --> 08:07.366
in the nose of the plane? No. We had cameras. We had 
one P-40 that eventually we tried to put a camera in

08:10.711 --> 08:16.378
to use as a reconnaissance airplane, but... The 
basis on which we claimed aircraft was the

08:16.797 --> 08:29.377
polished word plus your wingman or another guy 
seeing it go down. That's the basis on which we

08:29.497 --> 08:32.402
claimed. Sometimes, I dare say there may have been 
a little bit of cheating on it, but I don't think

08:32.422 --> 08:38.491
there was very much. I know this, the number that we 
shot down. For instance, the British

08:43.018 --> 08:44.661
intelligence When we evacuated Burma and, you 
know, then finally ran the Japanese down, the

08:45.637 --> 09:04.984
British intelligence claimed that there were 
almost 600 Japanese airplanes, wrecked

08:45.637 --> 09:04.984
airplanes, found in the southern part of Burma, 
and I know we didn't claim over 120 or something

08:45.637 --> 09:04.984
like that. But, now when these bombers saw you, 
when these ten bombers saw you, did they, did they

09:14.476 --> 09:17.619
try to put up a fight and get to their bombing 
objective? Or did they just turn and run? They

09:18.820 --> 09:24.245
mainly made a gradual turn, stayed in perfect 
formation. They never broke formation. I give

09:25.507 --> 09:26.388
credit for that. Boy, they stayed right in 
formation. See, that's the only defense. Of

09:29.611 --> 09:33.254
course, we'd pick the guys off from each end. We'd 
pick the last man on the Vs. Yeah, because they did

09:33.274 --> 09:42.643
have a little return rear-firing gun in a bucket 
that fell down and went back. The rear gunner would

09:42.824 --> 09:44.365
shoot back. you get behind, you know, get in the 
middle of the V, trying to shoot down the middle one

09:45.593 --> 10:11.289
down, you've got all this fire, where if you come on 
the end, my favorite tactics, and many others did

09:45.593 --> 10:11.289
the same thing, was to get way out, you know, where 
you have altitude, and come down, get, come down

09:45.593 --> 10:11.289
next to him, was to get, pick up speed, and then come 
up at a lower, about a lower quarter attack, and

09:45.593 --> 10:11.289
shoot, and then break off. That was my favorite 
tactic. And that was my best gunnery. had my

10:16.660 --> 10:31.419
gunnery, had I been, you know, had time to be really 
trained, had I been a typical fighter train pilot,

10:16.660 --> 10:31.419
like the average American fighter pilot, I'm sure 
I could have had 50 to 60 airplanes of my credit. But

10:31.439 --> 10:34.724
I just wasn't trained in gunnery, aerial gunnery. 
See, I was, ever since I graduated, I was in B-17.

10:40.231 --> 10:45.097
Uh, so you people did see four drop, and those were 
the last four. Uh, Well, that's when we broke off

