don't think we lost any on that.

12:09.925 --> 12:12.648
Sandy began calling us off and wagging his wings 
for joining us. By this time, we were some 200 miles

12:12.668 --> 12:15.512
from Columbia. Oh, I see. So you were 200 miles. 14 
of us had taken off. Okay. And we couldn't afford to

12:20.398 --> 12:23.321
lose any aircraft after such a fight.

12:28.207 --> 12:29.328
We found a base landing. The strike was followed in 
one by one.

12:37.478 --> 12:38.920
We had critiqued the detail. We could treat the 
flame, detail included. We had gotten four of the

12:41.327 --> 12:43.909
bombers ashore and several more as probable. I 
felt fairly convinced of having contributed to

12:44.289 --> 12:49.034
the loss of that left wingman. We were in high 
spirits, snarled with the ladies. It was our first

12:50.776 --> 12:53.378
test of combat and our first test. We had not lost a 
man. Not a man, no one, no wounded, or no, uh, right?

12:59.504 --> 13:01.746
No.

