13:41.641 --> 13:43.887
you Chenault was really happy with you. Oh, yeah. 
And that reminds me, let me make one comment before

13:44.308 --> 13:49.082
I close. I know you're going to ask this question. 
Sure, go right ahead. You know what?

14:21.179 --> 14:26.965
Now this is subsequent to, this one I was down in 
Rangoon later on, but I just want to make this

14:21.179 --> 14:26.965
comment to you now. This was in a fight, I think my 
first fight with Japanese fighters. Well, we're

14:32.271 --> 14:34.113
going to go through all of these. We're going to 
continue on these missions.

14:40.520 --> 14:42.743
Well, this is when I shot down three airplanes in 
combat. Well, we're going to get to that.

14:48.409 --> 14:49.110
Unbelievable. This is our only day. 
Unbelievable. Yet, I subsequently was to see the

14:51.081 --> 14:55.205
same lopsided victories over and over. Expertise 
from training, confidence, and high morale is a

14:55.986 --> 15:02.773
hard combination to beat. When experience is 
added, one becomes super.

15:09.479 --> 15:15.445
To me, that's the explanation of the flying tiger.

15:15.465 --> 15:17.186
We were unbeatable and we knew it. And It wasn't 
Glenn's fault.

15:24.094 --> 15:28.080
That first mission must have really blew them 
around. Well, of course, right after that, the

15:29.081 --> 15:37.134
boys at Rangoon began to get locked in combat 
practically every day. They'd come up with

15:38.957 --> 15:45.507
figures, you know, at the end of the day with nobody 
lost and maybe

15:50.397 --> 15:55.265
maybe 15 shot that. I think one day we shot down 21 
airplanes and ran through them, 21 Japanese and

15:55.285 --> 16:03.938
didn't lose a man. That's in four days of four 
different fights. Well we're going to get to that

16:06.462 --> 16:07.644
now. The first mission you had was the 20th of 
December, what was the next one? For me, well

16:24.316 --> 16:30.464
I don't actually remember getting in a fight with, 
I've scrambled on some flights up at Cunnameen. By

16:30.684 --> 16:33.708
the way, the bomber didn't come over for about two 
or three weeks after that. No. About two or three,

16:36.192 --> 16:38.555
ten days or anything. I remember scrambling 
against- Did he ever hit the city? Never hit the

16:41.679 --> 16:44.062
city again. No. One time about three- Did he ever 
drop any bombs on the city? No. One time about, must

16:47.687 --> 16:53.074
have been April or May. where we were dispersed at 
Chongqing and Kuilin and practically no

16:53.662 --> 16:57.948
airplanes would come in. I think they made a run up 
there and did actually hit the city with two or

16:58.429 --> 17:04.217
three bombers one night. But to answer your 
question about the next fight, I was on several

17:06.340 --> 17:19.078
scrambles out of Kunming where we know bombers 
were on their way up, but they never got to the city

17:06.340 --> 17:19.078
and we never saw them. I don't think I had actual 
contact with the enemy until following late

17:19.278 --> 17:30.917
January when my squadron, or I was, most of my 
squadron was picked to go to Rangoon. Okay. Late

17:33.661 --> 17:35.464
January 1942. At

17:35.484 --> 17:41.194
Rangoon. Tell me about that.

17:59.373 --> 18:28.080
On the...

17:59.373 --> 18:28.080
January the 29th, 1942

17:59.373 --> 18:28.080
was

17:59.373 --> 18:28.080
my first fight at Rangoon and this is when one of 
those typical fights. This is a typical fight we

18:30.203 --> 18:38.395
had at Rangoon and we, our squadron was there until 
the 27th or 28th of February at which time we had to

18:30.203 --> 18:38.395
evacuate. We would fight two to four times a day 
actually meeting the Japanese. I'd say about four

18:44.383 --> 18:46.767
or five times out of each week. And this was what I'm 
about to describe to you. It would be a typical

18:52.155 --> 18:54.558
combat, typical fight. We had a We were at 
Mingledon Air Base, RAF base at Rangoon, and we had

18:58.402 --> 19:25.370
the benefit of an RAF radar that was installed 
nearby to warn of the Japanese coming across from

18:58.402 --> 19:25.370
the full main Singapore

18:58.402 --> 19:25.370
mainland area.

19:25.390 --> 19:25.810
We would take every airplane off we could get off. 
And it'd be anywhere from, say, 8 to 10, maybe 12

19:30.355 --> 19:37.300
sometimes. Plus, the British could touch, but 
they'd have maybe two or three boosters or three or

19:37.320 --> 19:42.785
four Hurricanes. They'd get them off. And we'd all 
scramble, get off just as fast as we could. And

19:47.409 --> 19:54.635
actually, I've seen flights thread each other at 
the intersection of the runway in our haste to get

19:47.409 --> 19:54.635
off. Personally, we never had an aircraft taken 
off. I remember taking off several times, and

19:57.599 --> 20:14.260
instead of going through the normal procedure of 
checking the mags, you know, right and left mags, I

19:57.599 --> 20:14.260
wouldn't do it because I knew darn well I'd have 
such a drop that I'd just have a little bit of doubts

19:57.599 --> 20:14.260
and I wouldn't take off. Who do you mean your mags? 
That's a magneto. Oh, okay. You check the engines.

20:18.706 --> 20:19.186
Okay, okay. And it's normal procedure, and this is 
a proper plane. Sure. And... I knew I wouldn't take

20:28.615 --> 20:29.716
off. I couldn't justify the takeoff, logically. 
Why? Because of bad engine. Oh. And possibility of

20:36.142 --> 20:39.625
it conking out on the air, then you lose the 
airplane. Sure. In other words, it did need some

20:40.766 --> 20:44.309
maintenance on it, tuning up or something. But 
just go ahead and take off. Whatever runs good

20:45.730 --> 20:47.331
enough, you know. And the minute you get off and get 
your wheels tucked up and get all the garbage

20:47.391 --> 20:54.237
tucked in, you know, and flying clean, you begin to 
relax a little. And, of course, then is when you're

20:54.257 --> 20:56.479
getting ready to get to fight. But then you begin to 
relax. That was the most tense minutes is to hear

20:58.788 --> 21:07.082
the scrambles fall. That's the shocking thing. 
Then rush to your airplane, hoping that you can get

21:08.845 --> 21:19.724
in the airplane, get everything on, get the 
engines to it, and get off that runway before the

21:08.845 --> 21:19.724
bomb maybe hits you or a strafe. That's the most 
tense part of any scramble. But then, the minute

21:22.852 --> 21:25.816
you get in the air, see, then you have 
maneuverability. Maybe you get out of the way, and

21:25.876 --> 21:27.558
you see them coming. And you haste to have a chance 
to fight back, because you can point your airplane

21:27.578 --> 21:31.844
at them and shoot. Then you begin to relax a little. 
And then, of course, we'd join up, get up. Then we'd

21:37.372 --> 21:41.538
immediately go to 20,000 feet, and then we'd start 
circling. And like I say, there'd be, well,

21:41.558 --> 21:45.723
there'd be at least a flight of four each. Now, if 
there was an extra two, he'd tack on maybe a flight

21:46.224 --> 21:50.530
of six. And the booster boys, maybe they'd be 
nearby with three or four airplanes, maybe two.

21:57.188 --> 22:04.378
And we'd be generally in the same area where we 
could at least, you know, catch a glimpse of one

21:57.188 --> 22:04.378
another. We wouldn't fly in tight formation. And 
eventually, one of us would see this swirling mass

22:06.681 --> 22:14.412
of Japanese fighters coming over on a fighter 
suite. And I, it looked straight at me. Just a

22:17.056 --> 22:18.779
straight, basically? Uh, yeah. And to catch us in 
combat in the air with the idea of whipping us,

22:19.265 --> 22:23.630
shooting us down. In other words, it was a battle, 
air battle, to eventually wipe us out. They always

22:28.096 --> 22:31.640
thought, I don't know why, they just never would 
learn. They always thought they could destroy us.

22:34.143 --> 22:35.625
They didn't figure we had many airplanes. And they 
were right. We didn't have many. But they just

22:38.188 --> 22:45.617
never did

22:38.188 --> 22:45.617
succeed in knocking us out where we couldn't fight 
back. And... there's no doubt we must have shaken

22:47.648 --> 22:50.671
them up morale-wise. We're bound to because of the 
odds. They knew what they lost. And yet every time

22:54.115 --> 22:57.859
they come over, we still have eight or ten 
airplanes up there. And you can imagine coming

22:57.879 --> 23:05.647
over with 120 airplanes, seeing eight airplanes 
against you, you know darn well, well, these guys

22:57.879 --> 23:05.647
can't have many more. If we just keep up this few 
days, we might lose some, but they're bound to lose

23:05.667 --> 23:10.853
those. Well, we never did. But this is the way we'd 
meet. And it'd be just a looked like a haggle of

23:18.175 --> 23:21.120
bees, a swarm of bees. No formation at all, but they 
would move. For them, for the Japanese, no

23:23.664 --> 23:26.848
formation at all. And they'd move toward, you 
know, always moving towards Rangoon, eventually

23:27.630 --> 23:36.003
in Gages. This is how it was on the 29th of January. 
Right. And somebody saw them, and then, of course,

23:40.850 --> 23:45.938
all of us... They'd give us direction by ground, 
you know, 10 miles north of Pei-Gu, which was a

23:46.745 --> 23:56.822
little town outside of Ran-Gun, or just east of the 
city, and at 18,000, something like that. We

23:56.842 --> 24:01.710
always knew they were around 18,000, so 
altitude-wise, we knew just about where to look.

24:02.932 --> 24:04.174
And eventually, all of us see them. Now, 
sometimes, one flight may never even see this.

24:08.041 --> 24:11.807
You'd think it's impossible with that many 
airplanes in the air. that guys wouldn't be able to

24:12.175 --> 24:16.101
see it, but sometimes you just don't do it. I've 
been up in the air, and sometimes I wouldn't see

24:16.502 --> 24:20.808
them. And boy, it just killed me when I would. It 
just killed me to come back. These guys had been

24:24.855 --> 24:26.377
fighting, and I hadn't seen them. We'd make a point 
to hoover over each other about this. But

24:30.564 --> 24:33.729
eventually we saw all these airplanes, and then 
we'd get in a fight. And again, it was the usual

24:33.789 --> 24:36.613
tactics. Coming down from above and this swirly 
massed airplane, these were little fighters,

24:37.184 --> 24:45.694
little fixed, these were not zeroes at first when 
we met. What were they? These were called I-96s and

24:46.254 --> 24:48.817
I-97s. They were little fixed wing Japanese 
fighters that reminded me of the early P-26. A

24:57.287 --> 25:06.077
little monoplane, low wing, fixed landing gear, 
real sharp looking airplane this day with a radial

24:57.287 --> 25:06.077
engine on it. very maneuverable. They could 
practically turn around in a common 50-foot lock.

25:12.608 --> 25:14.511
What about armament? They had two little 
7.5-millimeter gun guns. That's all? Very light

25:18.275 --> 25:19.176
armament. And practically, I don't know whether 
they even had an armor plate in them or not. How

25:22.080 --> 25:22.781
about speed? Oh, very low compared to the P-40. 
They'd probably cruise. They were an easy prey,

25:27.467 --> 25:28.248
then. Oh, yes. These were. These were. But 
extremely maneuverable. And if you ever let them

25:32.333 --> 25:35.317
get on your tail, then you've had a problem. You've 
just been out couldn't possibly out-turn them.

25:38.587 --> 25:40.769
But you could out-power them. Oh, yeah. So, you 
know, you do tactics. We'd come down and pick one of

25:42.992 --> 25:46.575
them on the end, on the outside of the squirrel. And 
I'd just grab mine, and my tactics were just like

25:47.756 --> 25:51.440
all the rest of them. And I'd come down, pick out one 
guy because of his position. I figured he'd be

25:55.304 --> 26:00.549
about in the right position for me to be on his tail 
when I got in firing position. And I'd just stay

26:00.569 --> 26:05.374
right with him, completely ignoring all the rest 
of them. And as I'd come in, There's your came in.

26:08.753 --> 26:10.275
Okay, you're describing a situation. Yeah, I'm 
coming in on the attack. As I get into position to

26:11.897 --> 26:24.052
shoot, say maybe four or five hundred yards, then 
close, with intention to close practically by

26:11.897 --> 26:24.052
running over it, then I start firing. And I had, as I 
say, a .430 caliber gun and a .250 caliber, hoping

26:24.072 --> 26:32.022
all of them

26:24.072 --> 26:32.022
would fire. Sometimes I'd hold my trigger down too 
long, and I'd fire too long a burst, and heat up my

26:32.339 --> 26:38.108
guns too fast. As a result, I'd have a stoppage on my 
gun and have to cock them again, you know, get them

26:38.668 --> 26:44.297
working again. For the 50s? For the 50s. Not for the 
30s. Well, the 30s, a lot of times they'd get

26:46.620 --> 26:53.170
stopped up, and I'd hit my, I'd go out of control, 
and it wouldn't unstop. Many times I'd go on back to

26:53.210 --> 26:57.957
the base, but none of them were for the 30s working 
at all. But not on this particular plane. No.

26:59.459 --> 27:00.661
You're moving in on this one. Oh, yeah. On this one 
bird on the outside. And I'd close in on him, and

27:03.110 --> 27:14.139
being a normal fighter pilot, he probably knew I 
was coming in on him, and he'd wait until the last

27:03.110 --> 27:14.139
minute to return. Sometimes he wouldn't. But in 
this particular case, now there's many of these I

27:15.801 --> 27:23.267
had, so I'll try to be, this is typical. But just 
give me this example. Coming in on this guy, he saw

27:26.890 --> 27:29.953
me. and turned at the last, very last, at the 
correct second. And I tried to follow, but as I

27:35.247 --> 27:43.015
followed, I'd gotten inside of this mess of 
airplanes, and no doubt there'd been some on my

27:35.247 --> 27:43.015
tail. So I chose not to follow, and I turned off. I 
didn't even get to fire my gun at him. But then I

27:47.840 --> 27:54.226
pulled off the side, gained a little more 
altitude, didn't turn around and come back in, did

27:47.840 --> 27:54.226
the same thing again. This time, I caught one about 
the same way, and I closed in on him and started

27:54.266 --> 28:00.312
firing. And I began to see smoke come off his 
airplane and boil down the side of his cockpit. And

28:07.589 --> 28:15.716
I remember practically, I felt as though I had to 
lift my left wing to get over his right wing as I

28:07.589 --> 28:15.716
passed by him. No kidding. And I looked back. You 
were that close? Oh, yeah. Oh, goodness. You could

28:19.920 --> 28:21.762
have touched him. Well, it seems that close, yeah. 
I'd say easily within 50 feet, no doubt. Did you see

28:28.267 --> 28:30.109
the pilot? No. One time I saw a pilot in an airplane. 
As a matter of fact, it was in the same flight. I

28:38.708 --> 28:43.615
looked back long enough to see this guy trailing 
off and smoke going down and I figured I got him.

28:45.358 --> 28:51.087
Then I remember that was the first airplane I shot 
down. What was your feeling?

28:59.185 --> 29:04.733
I squealed into the light and caught myself 
laughing aloud, sitting there in my cockpit at

28:59.185 --> 29:04.733
some 18,000 feet. Enough for him. Got one. There 
you are, Hoffman, old boy. Just a few days before we

29:10.060 --> 29:13.485
lost Hoffman in a fight with the Japs. He was one of 
the oldest, as a matter of fact, he was the oldest

29:13.525 --> 29:19.794
boy we had from the Navy. And he was in the other 
squadron and was one of the first pilots we lost in

29:19.814 --> 29:25.441
combat. I think we only lost eight. And That was my 
reaction. Related?

29:34.052 --> 29:40.177
It's a hell of a thing to say you're related about 
killing somebody, but related doesn't describe

29:34.052 --> 29:40.177
it. I was exuberant. I was just beside myself. And 
then, of course, I wanted more. So then I pulled off

29:46.743 --> 29:51.287
again to come back. So you banged off him. Yeah, 
yeah. And he was going down. Yeah, to do the same

29:55.371 --> 29:56.692
thing. And of course, all this time, You could look 
across the whole area and you could see, you could

29:58.720 --> 30:05.386
see smoke, streaming smoke of airplanes going 
down. You could actually see, catch out of the

30:05.846 --> 30:12.292
ground, burning airplanes. This is just a mass 
dogfight like you might see in the old movies. And

30:18.377 --> 30:25.183
the next one, I believe the next one was a head-on 
attack. Yeah. I came in and I was going to do my same

30:27.172 --> 30:33.220
little stunt, catching the guy on the end and all. 
But just about time as I was approaching to get in my

30:33.580 --> 30:43.493
firing run, I caught another Jap that evidently 
had seen me and knew what I was going to do. And all of

30:44.033 --> 30:49.320
a sudden here he appeared right in front of me and we 
were hitting directly at each other. And it was

30:51.082 --> 30:53.365
close enough to shoot, so both of us started 
shooting. I could see, you know, when you shoot

30:53.834 --> 30:59.501
your gun, the smoke curls over the wings, 
trailing, and you see the smoke. He was shooting at

30:59.521 --> 31:01.164
me, and I was shooting at him. And I didn't feel 
anything hitting me, but I knew I was hitting him

31:01.845 --> 31:17.285
because I began to see smoke curling coming from 
the Indian cow along the two sides of the airplane.

31:17.305 --> 31:21.310
And at the very last second, I was going to pull up. 
But the very last second, apparently, he was going

31:22.488 --> 31:25.992
to pull up and did. And I don't know how to describe 
it, but just split second thing, you know. And I

31:32.179 --> 31:35.923
started to pull up and then shoved forward 
violently. And when I shoved forward, of course,

31:35.983 --> 31:40.688
that's a negative force. And except for my seat 
belt, I'd have thrown myself right through the

31:40.708 --> 31:44.732
canopy, I'm sure, if it wasn't violent. But my head 
hit the canopy. But everything turned black. as

31:50.315 --> 31:53.159
his airplane passed over me, that's how close he 
was. So we couldn't have missed each other more

31:53.600 --> 31:59.327
than, we couldn't have missed each other more than 
20, 25 feet, even closer. And then, of course, turn

32:00.529 --> 32:06.838
around and look at him, and I saw him going down, and 
I was close enough where I claimed him. Just like

32:08.720 --> 32:09.401
the other one. He went down there right after that. 
Oh, yeah, oh, yeah. Matter of fact, I think I

32:12.345 --> 32:15.129
followed him down a little. And I was, I remember I 
was so tense and tight that, you know, just hardly

32:19.745 --> 32:21.808
breathing. And then, not exuberant, but, you 
know, just tense. And then as I watched him go down,

32:27.315 --> 32:34.085
then I began to relax, and I started to get elated 
and exuberant again. God damn, two or something

32:34.285 --> 32:37.269
like that. And then, after I was over, I started 
again, and this time I... They just keep doing

32:44.239 --> 32:47.984
this. That's their formation. Why didn't they 
stay in the middle? Why didn't they move out? Why

32:53.908 --> 32:58.533
did they stick together just as a beehive?

32:59.554 --> 33:03.459
Seemingly mutually supporting one another. And 
of course we just picked off the side of them. Sure.

33:08.144 --> 33:09.345
Especially with a quicker flying. Yeah, and then 
the next one I think was similar to the first one

33:09.405 --> 33:13.710
where I got him on a rear attack. And by this time... 
Tell me about that. Tell me about this. Well, it's

33:19.825 --> 33:20.866
similar to the first. I think I caught him from the 
rear. And, oh, this is when I came past him, and our

33:23.389 --> 33:37.125
speed differentiation was so small that I 
actually passed him and could see him sitting in

33:23.389 --> 33:37.125
fire in a cockpit. But, you know, just a quick pass 
to look over. Say about 50 feet apart. So you came up

33:41.010 --> 33:43.312
behind him. Yes. Similar to the first one, yeah. 
And how far were you when you started shooting?

33:51.222 --> 33:54.186
Oh, again, probably four or five hundred yards. 
And then you just close up, you know, practically

33:54.206 --> 33:56.349
run over him. And then he got to move over to get by 
him. And he was obviously, I obviously killed him,

33:58.472 --> 34:06.323
you know, way back because he didn't make any 
effort to move at all. He just stayed right in the

34:06.364 --> 34:11.671
same position, smoke coming back, black smoke, 
and then he started going down real slow. And as I

34:11.691 --> 34:13.013
passed by him, He was sitting in fire in the 
cockpit. He was on fire? Oh yeah, he was dead.

34:18.450 --> 34:20.713
Otherwise, he was bailed out. Sure. I don't ever 
remember seeing Daphne bail out. What did you feel

34:29.925 --> 34:32.728
like when you saw this man on fire? Well, I just 
exuberant again. You know,

34:35.932 --> 34:42.460
you don't get like a... a madman you just get by then 
you get coldly calculating daring

34:43.199 --> 35:10.270
confident you know you can do it sure

34:43.199 --> 35:10.270
you're you've won nothing can hold you back it's 
feeling of winning in As a combat pilot, a pilot has

35:10.807 --> 35:13.912
a feeling of being victorious. You're good. 
You've done your job. And you just feel elated. Not

35:21.623 --> 35:22.224
nervous. The actual firing and attacking and 
seeing him on fire, it's tense. But it's just like

35:33.160 --> 35:35.043
I'm telling you, it's fitness. But then when you, 
the afterthought or before is when you get tense.

35:38.853 --> 35:41.777
and nervous about it, and a little bit scared 
maybe. Of course, in between these attacks I'm

35:43.018 --> 35:54.533
telling you about, I actually had made some 
attacks and had to break it off because I found

35:43.018 --> 35:54.533
airplanes on my tail, but they weren't close 
enough to hit me. You were out of their range. Oh,

35:56.695 --> 35:57.036
yeah. You continually, continually got your head 
on a pedestal. If a guy doesn't get on your tail, you

36:00.760 --> 36:06.247
can't get shot down. That's the old days. It 
doesn't in the day for missiles, but in the old days

36:08.182 --> 36:10.925
for guns. It's true. Subsequently, in the story 
later on, I didn't do that and I got shot at. But by

36:16.432 --> 36:20.597
that time, you know, we were nearing the end of 
combat. The airplanes, you don't see many of your

36:20.677 --> 36:31.469
P-40s around and their flights broken up more and 
they started back, they make this swoop at 180

36:20.677 --> 36:31.469
degrees and they're going back home. So, you know, 
the fight's over. You just have, you know when to

36:32.911 --> 36:34.593
quit. So, how long did the fight take? You shot 
three down that day. That whole flight probably

36:39.472 --> 36:42.595
took thirty-five minutes. That's all?

36:46.138 --> 36:51.203
The longest time it takes is to climb the altitude, 
get there, then when you see them, all that time. I

36:53.225 --> 37:06.758
dare say the actual

36:53.225 --> 37:06.758
combat shooting those three airplanes, and 
probably one problem, actually the three

36:53.225 --> 37:06.758
airplanes, one problem was it probably took— Tell 
me about the problem. It's one I wasn't sure of.

37:08.669 --> 37:10.172
Probably the same type of attack. I'd have to read 
this to...

37:16.842 --> 37:17.964
It's the same type of attack. Okay, but the whole 
thing takes about 35 minutes. The whole thing

37:21.570 --> 37:27.480
takes about 35 minutes, but the actual fighting, 
engaging, couldn't take over 10 minutes. Except

37:29.062 --> 37:31.125
for 8 minutes. That's always the way it is. And then 
when you get down, you know, then of course, we're

37:32.742 --> 37:39.351
not in formation with each other, but when you 
start breaking off a meeting, you start looking

37:32.742 --> 37:39.351
for a buddy. And no matter who it is, if it's P-40, 
you go up and get together. You join. He may have

37:44.217 --> 37:47.342
been your wingman, now you're flying on his wing, 
but you get together. And then you start going back

37:47.382 --> 37:56.894
to the base, and we'd arrive back to the base in 
twos, ones, threes, and, you know, very seldom,

37:47.382 --> 37:56.894
very seldom in the same, if ever. I can, well, maybe 
one or two, I return to the base with, maybe my

38:01.598 --> 38:06.383
wingman on the same position, but very, very 
seldom. Now, this is the... Oh, did the Japanese

38:06.403 --> 38:10.448
just start moving away then? Then they go back 
home. I mean, they had decided they'd had enough,

38:12.030 --> 38:15.534
right? So did they make up their mind at this 
particular battle on the 29th of January, did they

38:15.554 --> 38:24.204
make up their mind first that they'd had enough, or 
did you people? Well, it's a tactic. See, they can

38:25.325 --> 38:31.572
only fly so far and so long because of fuel, but 
can't last too long, and... We know that, and they

38:31.889 --> 38:33.411
know it. So it's almost a set pattern. You don't 
just...

38:39.499 --> 38:47.410
The time element is always in your mind, and where 
you are, the navigation, has to always be in your

38:39.499 --> 38:47.410
mind, or you'll never make it back. Or you'll run 
out of gas. So it's just automatically when you

38:49.172 --> 38:52.837
break off. And it's experience. It's experience. 
And then we get back, and of course we...

39:00.998 --> 39:15.817
Sometimes, if there's no worries about more 
attacks or more waves of bombers or fighters

39:00.998 --> 39:15.817
coming over, we'd by ourselves, we'd come over to 
the field and do a slow roll, a victory roll, pull up

39:00.998 --> 39:15.817
and land. Then we'd get down, of course, we'd get 
together and have a critique and discuss all of

39:16.238 --> 39:21.825
that. That's the way, by the end of one day, I forget 
when it was, it was the latter part of February,

39:22.042 --> 39:30.913
we'd been fighting about four, we'd fought the 
Japanese four times in one day. And you see, this

39:31.394 --> 39:35.579
was toward the end of the campaign when they were 
about, well, they did force us out. See, the

39:35.599 --> 39:36.961
intensity was such. And they achieved their 
objective, they forced us out. We just drew the

39:41.126 --> 39:42.889
rate from Rangoon. Then the ground forces, see, 
were moving forward too. So if we'd stayed there

39:45.552 --> 39:51.019
another 24 hours, we may not have got our ground 
force up the highway enough. We actually

39:51.455 --> 40:00.506
patrolled them the day we evacuated to be sure that 
if any Japanese coming across the ground were

39:51.455 --> 40:00.506
attacked, we'd at least give them some air 
support.

